</h3><p class="sc-hOGkXu hVdrsp pf-91_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Goleman's concept also brings an evolutionary perspective to the table. He suggests that the skills integral to a business may have roots in our primitive past – barter, craftsmanship, and negotiation. This evolutionary backdrop not only adds depth to the concept but also suggests that these skills are, in some sense, hardwired and universal, honed and refined over millennia.
</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-furwcr dAWGlU pf-93_ pf-r pf-c-cm pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:6;--c-md:6;--c-lg:6"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-fHeRUh cCunWv pf-94_"><h3 tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-kHOZwM hRBLBR pf-95_">Learning and mastery: A lifelong process
</h3><p class="sc-hOGkXu hVdrsp pf-97_" tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Business Intelligence is not an innate gift but a learnable skill set. Goleman points out that signs of business talent often appear early in life and are honed over time. This perspective democratises the concept – it's not the preserve of a gifted few but a potential in many, waiting to be developed through experience, education, and reflection.
